segments.text: That going to the chancellor's office would require hour upon hour of work and going far beyond the eight to five format.
And I felt that Peggy, with one of her sons becoming a senior in high school that year, would have difficulty in keeping
the clock calendar that would be essential in the chancellor's office.
Also, Peggy had been with the College of Education since its beginning.
and was in fact the thread that runs so true through much of the college's activities and would help the new dean, whoever he or she might be, in a fashion that would be essential.
In the president's, in the chancellor's office when I arrived,
There was an elder Raoul, an assistant to the chancellor, who again was a veteran on the campus and knew the history of the campus and all of its political machinations very, very well.
She was a big help.
A Shirley Lightfoot was a secretary, and her secretarial skills were just unmatched.
I don't know of anyone who could do correspondence as rapidly and as accurately as she kept it.
There was another young lady.
a graduate of St. Edward's in Austin.
I think she's now with the vice president or vice chancellor for agriculture, Patricia Gehring.
Again, a very talented young woman.
That was in the immediate office staff.
Surrounding me, other than Bob Cherry and Clyde Freeman and Peel, was also on the chancellor's staff, James Bond, the attorney for the system.
James had the advantage of knowing the
of knowing the area of education quite well.
He had had actually more experience before coming on board as attorney for the system.
He had had more experience in public education than he had in higher education.
To my knowledge, I know that he had been a member of the Board of Trustees of the Navasota School District.
And Jim was a big help.
I look upon Jim as sort of a student of Clyde Freeman's.
Clyde Freeman taught James an immense amount of background information regarding the Attorney General's office, opinions of the Attorney General.
budget procedures, the permanent and available university funds, and James was a good student.
He learned them well.
They were the main ones.
Some of your student products in whom you take great pride, like Brian Cole and others.
Yes, yes.
My number one
choice for a student who who succeeded admirably was a chap by the name of Jack Humphreys.
Jack came to me as an assistant registrar at Sam Houston State University.
I had a call from the president of that institution saying Frank
Have a young man over here, assistant registrar.
He has a master's degree in history from Baylor.
Really an outstanding scholar and student.
He's far above being an assistant registrar.
He needs to get his doctorate degree and do things other than what he's doing now.
Can you help him?
I said, have him come over and visit with me.
He did.
Tremendously impressive chap.
Articulate, poised.
knowledgeable, highly intelligent, excellent vocabulary, wrote well.
I asked him to immediately to be a graduate assistant in my office.
He accepted, later on became assistant dean, and then associate dean, and by the time he finished his PhD degree, he was truly a remarkable person.
I think Jack,
had not only my high praise, but he was highly respected by the heads of departments in the college, both of liberal arts and of education.
Jack was astute, tactful, diplomatic in his relationships with the administrators in the colleges and was a tremendously big help.
Went back to Sam Houston as dean of their liberal arts section.
Stayed a couple of three years there, then was chosen by Southern Ross State University as president.
Operated very effectively in that office.
Revived that institution giving program by rejuvenating its development foundation and was very successful there.
Sadly enough, Jack had cancer.
And after a year's stay in Houston on leave from Sol Ross, he and his wife and family moved to Houston with him.
He had a wife and two sons.
Jack died of the cancer.
Sad, sad, sad young man.
Another choice of mine was another lad who made college presidency, and this was David Johnson, a Negro from Tyler,
who became president of Texas College in Tyler, a Methodist-related church, school, small liberal arts college, struggling for survival.
David did well, and strangely enough, too, during his term as president,
He was identified as a cancer patient and died of that disease.
So that was sad.
Another one whom I would point to with great pride is Linda Whitson.
Linda was an outstanding woman student in the graduate program.
Thorough, statistically very sharp,
an attractive lady, quite handsome in fact, always so well-groomed, articulate, but quiet.
There wasn't an aggressive inclination, I think, in her makeup, but so thorough in the things that she did.
After she received her doctorate, I received a call from the president of the University of Texas at San Antonio asking me about her.
She had applied for a job over there and was accepted for it and became vice president at the University of Texas San Antonio for business matters, I think.
Well, a phase of business, personnel matters and things of that nature.
I don't think she was the dollar number cruncher, but the area of personnel relations, she was there and, as I understand, had an outstanding record.
I would mention those three as outstanding, along with Brian Cole, who also was an associate dean.
When he finished with me, he was from Marlin, Texas.
Brian came to A&M.
It was he who followed Jack Humphries in the office.
And Brian was a veteran of the Vietnamese operation.
His undergraduate work had been done at the United States Military Academy on the Hudson, West Point.
And just a very, very fine man.
exceptionally well-trained individual.
Brian was assistant and then a graduate assistant, then assistant dean, then an associate dean, and was simply outstanding in the work which he performed.
Was the immediate past chancellor one of your doctoral students?
Who?
The immediate past chancellor.
Oh, Barry Thompson?
Barry.
Was he one of your students?
No.
I have a connection with Barry, but it was not in a student relationship.
These first four that I've mentioned, I chaired their doctoral committees.
That's what I perceive you mean by a student.
Right, right.
Barry Thompson was, I knew him primarily as the son of his father.
I knew his father quite well.
Tommy Thompson, superintendent of schools at Kermit, Texas for many years.
A legend among Texas school administrators.
Truly outstanding guy.
Barry had come up through the public education route.
I'd met him along the way several times.
and learned from him during a conversation when he came to campus that he wanted to complete his graduate work at A&M.
and do a doctorate there with us.

And he says, I've got to find, at that moment, he was assistant superintendent of schools for the Waco Independent School District in charge of their curricular matters, assistant superintendent for curriculum.
And his salary, I expect, was a pretty good salary at that time.
And he said, Dean Hubert, I simply
My family, I would put my family to an unjustified position if I asked them to try to live on the salary of a graduate assistant.
So if you have anything in the future that you see developing that you could help me in a job here at A&M, I'd appreciate it.

Well, I knew of his high anxiety to finish the doctorate, and so there came a time when I was able to upgrade one of the graduate assistantships associated with my office to the point that Barry could live on it for a year with his family.
And he did, and it was through that that he completed his residency at A&M.
He already was a student, commuting student, but he had to have a year's residency, and it was my finding him that position that enabled him to complete that.
So that was my basic association with him.
I did not share his doctoral committee, nor was I a member of it.
But that's the relationship.
In your 30 years, more than 30 years of official relation with Texas A&M and the A&M system, which directors, and then their title was changed to regents, deserve the greatest credit?
Total time at A&M High School, twenty-three years.
Oh, my math wrong.
Fifty-nine to eighty-two.
That's right, my math wrong, yeah.
Now, which regents or directors deserve the greatest credit?
Well, starting with the directors group, one would first have to place Sterling Evans at the top of the list, without any doubt.
Although Sterling, I think, had been through the agricultural degree program at A&M, nonetheless, he was far ahead
of many of his colleagues on the board in support of a broad-based, well-balanced university.
He was just as supportive of engineering, of the arts and sciences, and of veterinary medicine as any others, probably more so for the arts and sciences.
He appreciated the essential necessity of communication skills,
of history, and he was a great supporter of that realm.
I would also name Dr. Boydle later on as a regent, who was an outstanding board member along with Gardner Simons.
who at that time was chairman of the board of tech of Tentaco Corporation, and who incidentally, I think, had served on the Stanford California Board of Regents or Trustees, by whatever name.
In his capacity as chief executive officer of a major corporation, he brought a new vision and foresight to the Board of Regents.
Sam Wittenberg from Amarillo, Texas.
I think a background in the newspaper field.
Wittenberg was a University of Texas graduate.
He was strongly interested in a strongly based university with power and
excellence in the humanities and social sciences and mathematics and physical sciences as was anyone else.
I would name those as outstanding ones which I remember.
Later on, more in my years as chancellor, I would have to name John Blocker.
As John Blocker was chief stockholder, chairman of the board, and president of Blocker Energy Corporation in Houston, it too was a major organization.
John was outstanding on the board.
as was Dr. John Coleman of Houston, a physician, a black individual.
He was there, I presume, as a political representative of Prairie View A&M.
I don't know that that's the truth, but he was interested in Prairie View
but not to the disadvantage of any other institution.
John was an outstanding board member.
Al Davies of Fort Worth, no, of Dallas.
Clyde Wells of Granbury.
Clyde held the chairmanship of the board of, I guess, directors and regents for a good long while.
Clyde was a manager of a large agricultural organization in Dallas.
Actually, their agricultural interests were out more in the Granbury area where his residence was.
He was good on the board and for the board.
Quiet, but effective.
Your proudest accomplishments in relationship to A&M?
Haskell, it's hard to identify one.
Well, it can be plural.
Among those that I was pleased with the outcome of were these.
In the first several years development of the College of Liberal Arts,
Science had broken out because science wanted its own identity.
Liberal arts, when it achieved its separate identity, seemed to move forward rapidly, both in scholarship of faculty, I think, as well as enrollment of students.
Another accomplishment that I was proud of was my chairmanship of the Coordinating Committee of the Century Council.
I think that enabled me to have some inputs into the deliberations of that organization which moved A&M forward.
Another would be the origination of the honors program at A&M.
After the big change took place, co-eds admitted, military no longer required.
One day, Dick Ballinger, a professor of English, visited with me and said, Dean Hubert, there's been a little talk in the English department.
about the desirability of starting an honors section in English.
We're getting some outstanding students, and we'd like to take them a little faster and further than our ordinary curriculum would.
How would you react to our establishing an honors program in English?"
I said, Dick, it's a great idea.
why don't we do it for the college and ask other departments if they'd like to join in establishing honors programs.
He said, fine.
I said, well, will you be the faculty sponsor of an honors program?
And he said, yes.
And that took off and was a success, I think.
In the College of Education, I would point to
the accreditation by the college and every one of its teacher education programs by the National Council for the Accreditation of Teacher Education.
It's most unusual on a first visit by this evaluation team from NCATE for that institution to be approved in every one of its offerings.
from baccalaureate through the doctorate, and A&M was.
And I think that's a case of where I simply happened to be there when it took place.
We had a great faculty, and they were the key elements in that accomplishment.
But it's one that I am quite proud of.
In the chancellor's office, Haskell, again, hard to say.
I thought my proposal for the reorganization of the system was sound in my single-track
way, I guess, of thinking of things.
I still think it was a good thing for the system, although I think it would take the Green Berets in full force armor to make it feasible again, politically feasible.
Those are some of the things along the way.
What's your favorite Aggie story?
Got to be some moment you remember that you loved.
Yes.
My favorite Aggie story is this one.
It's used as an illustration.
during what I call the golden years of A&M, just how dramatically that institution turned around.
From being recognized by high school students somewhere out there as a, as a cow college, on through up to becoming a full-fledged major university.
And it's a story that goes like this.
Education at A&M has changed dramatically.
In fact, over the past 20 or 25 years, it has come full circle, 180 degree change.
For example, at A&M 25 years ago, all the Aggies were telling moron jokes.
And today,
That's my favorite story.
If you mean an Aggie joke story, that's my favorite one.
What advice would you give to the leaders of A&M today about what the role, I'll use the phrase role and scope, what advice would you give the leaders of A&M today, be they board members or
administrators, the role and scope of Texas A&M University, what should it be?
I would suggest to them that first they should study carefully the history of the university.
Look at it from day one and over the past 100 and what, 10, 15 years now, I'm not sure,
114 years.
Find out what brought it from its beginnings to where it is today.
Know something about the essence of a land-grant college and the fact that

The original premise behind a land-grant college hasn't been abandoned, but the change in the nature of our nation has taken us to the point where a true college-university type institution must go far beyond
the emphasis upon agriculture and the mechanical arts.
That would be my first recommendation for leaders of the university.
I would suggest next that
That they seek good advice if they are not attuned to the various components of a top university.
Seek good advice and know what questions to ask of whom.
Knowing which question to ask and to whom to address that question is exceedingly important for administrators, governing board members, faculty members, and all of us.
I think those would be my two major recommendations.
Know the history, seek good advice, and know what questions to ask.
Okay, one light question and then two serious questions and we're finished.
The light question is did any students or anybody else ever try to play any jokes or pranks on you as a teacher, as an administrator?
Not that I recall.
Nobody in class tried to set one up or anything?
No.
Okay.
All right.
Next to last question.
Looking back, what effect has it had on your life that you came to Texas A&M in 1959?
Well, it's had a...
It's had a very dominant role in my life after A&M.
It has brought me to a recognition that this community is an important community.
This university is an important university.
must not take the short view.
They need to look well into the future.
